node.text:
Some people search their whole lives for great friends, 
& some great friends... make you search! 
.
We've kept busy during this lock down with yoga, trivia, dance classes, coffee times, games, & getting to know each other.  You learn more about a person in the months spent onboard together 24/7 than years put into building the same lifelong friendships on land.  So when these friends leave, their absence is felt like a hole in the heart. 

But in true QuaranTeam style, my pals didn't go quietly.  They left behind a scavenger hunt full of memories, a lot of laughter and a ton of tears.
Dr. Seuss said it best:
“Don’t cry because it’s over. Smile because it happened.”
Thank you for the countless smiles.  Thank you for being "family".
.

node.text:
When it comes to repatriating our crew, Celebrity has been doing everything they can to get them home. This is a glimpse into just a small part of the preparation for Operation Hope.
. 
Because we can't fly on commercial aircraft from the US, creative solutions are key. 
Each day presents a modified operation or requirement. 
The first step is identifying who needs to go, where, & when. Flights & relievers must be arranged. Then it's the details of "The New Norm" (i.e. PCR tests) which have to be arranged. 
. 
This is how it went down yesterday:
A plane arrives in Coco Cay from Nassau at 10 a.m. with COVID Tests kits. 
We sail to Coco Cay & retrieve them from the pier using our rescue boat. 
We sail back to the anchorage.
Using our launches, we transfer the tests to the Summit, Equinox, & Silhouette.
The tests are conducted onboard and the launches collect them back and return to the Edge.
We sail back to Coco Cay.
The rescue boat is launched and the tests are delivered to the pier where the plane picks them up for Nassau at 4 p.m.
We sail back to the anchorage.
The plan from there was to transfer the tested crew to the Equinox which would take them to Freeport to fly to Fort Lauderdale, then Miami, then Atlanta or JFK, and then across the pond.
. 
Sounds simple, right? However 2.5 hours after we finished the 8 hour operation, the Bahamas ceased outgoing flights to the US, effective immediately.
That's back to the drawing board & by this afternoon we already have another solid plan in place thanks to Celebrity thinking outside of the box with Plan X. 
So yesterday wasn't a total wash. We had plenty of opportunities for training & maneuvers, of which our Chief Officer Maria had 8, including her first anchor drop!
.

A double rainbow is the reward when 40 knots of wind pops up on the beam in a random squall while making the final approach to the pier.
The Edge is a beast with 19k horsepower thrusters & 10 MW's of available power, but the most powerful thing about this ship is the teamwork. The cool, calm, collected support that I get whether it's a straightforward maneuver or a more challenging one.
.
Today, we're all better officers & crew, because of the people around us. 
.
